Problem: in {{aui-date-picker.js}}, at the end of the private method {{initCalendar()}}, a {{keydown}} event handler is added to the {{<body>}} element (at line 120 in my copy):

{code:javascript}
    $('body').on('keydown', handleDatePickerFocus);
{code}

This event listener is never removed, even if {{destroyPolyfill()}} is called explicitly. (The same {{function handleDatePickerFocus}} is also registered as a handler for other events, and those seem to be removed when needed.) If an application dynamically creates date pickers on demand, these event listeners accumulate, even if the date pickers are otherwise destroyed and removed from the document. (Also, the listener becomes orphaned when {{reset()}} is called, and a new one is added during the first {{show()}}.)

What’s worse is that orphan event listeners will actually throw an exception if triggered after {{destroyPolyfill()}}, because {{destroyPolyfill()}} deletes the {{hide()}} method (at line 207 in my copy), but {{handleDatePickerFocus()}} — the event handler — calls it without checking if it exists anymore. Only one exception is thrown per event, even if multiple orphan listeners are attached, because the exception interrupts event dispatching. The bad news is that legitimate event listeners later in the dispatch queue don’t get the event anymore, either.

Note: This concerns the file {{aui-date-picker.js}} from the {{com.atlassian.auiplugin:aui-date-picker}} web-resource. The debugging I did was on a dev-mode JIRA instance with version {{v7.0.0#70107-sha1:6cd5e8d}}, but I’m pretty sure it affects any product using the AUI date picker. I’ve looked at [AUI 5.9.17|https://docs.atlassian.com/aui/5.9.17/docs/date-picker.html], and it seems to have the same issue.

